hands_on_practices.problem:
The vibrational energy levels, $G(v)$, of a diatomic molecule can be approximated by the expression $G(v) = 	ilde{
u}_e (v + 1/2) - 	ilde{
u}_e x_e (v + 1/2)^2$, where $v$ is the vibrational quantum number (a non-negative integer), $	ilde{
u}_e$ is the harmonic vibrational frequency, and $	ilde{
u}_e x_e$ is the anharmonicity constant. Both $	ilde{
u}_e$ and $	ilde{
u}_e x_e$ are expressed in units of wavenumbers ($	ext{cm}^{-1}$).

An undergraduate student performs infrared spectroscopy on a sample of a diatomic gas. The spectrum reveals a strong absorption band corresponding to the fundamental transition (from $v=0$ to $v=1$) centered at a wavenumber of $2886 	ext{ cm}^{-1}$. A much weaker absorption band, corresponding to the first overtone transition (from $v=0$ to $v=2$), is observed at $5668 	ext{ cm}^{-1}$.

Using this experimental data, calculate the harmonic vibrational frequency, $	ilde{
u}_e$, of the molecule. Express your answer in units of $	ext{cm}^{-1}$, rounded to four significant figures.
